This is a great question because you're no longer asking "How do I use Queue?" You're asking "What concepts do I need to know for Queue, just like I know Comparable, Comparator, equals(), hashCode() for List, Set, and Map?"

The answer is yes, every collection has its own important concepts.

Think of the Collection Framework like this
1. List (Ordered Collection)

Main concepts you must know:

✅ Index-based access
✅ Duplicate elements allowed
✅ Collections.sort()
✅ Comparable
✅ Comparator
✅ equals()
✅ Iterator
✅ ListIterator
✅ ArrayList internal working
✅ LinkedList internal working
✅ Time complexities
2. Set (Unique Collection)

Main concepts:

✅ hashCode()
✅ equals()
✅ Comparable (for TreeSet)
✅ Comparator (for TreeSet)
✅ HashSet internal working
✅ LinkedHashSet insertion order
✅ TreeSet (Red-Black Tree)
✅ Iterator
✅ Time complexities
3. Map (Key-Value Collection)

Main concepts:

✅ Key-Value pairs
✅ Map.Entry
✅ entrySet()
✅ keySet()
✅ values()
✅ hashCode()
✅ equals()
✅ Comparable (for TreeMap keys)
✅ Comparator (for TreeMap keys)
✅ HashMap buckets
✅ Hash collisions
✅ Load factor
✅ Resizing
✅ Time complexities
4. Queue (This is your next topic)

Queue has a completely different purpose.

Its main idea is processing order, not sorting.

Think of people standing in a line at a ticket counter.

Front

A
B
C
D

Rear

The first person to enter is the first person to leave.

This is called:

FIFO (First In, First Out).

Queue concepts you should master
A. FIFO
offer(10);
offer(20);
offer(30);

Queue:

Front

10
20
30

Rear

Remove:

poll();

Output:

10

Now:

20
30
B. Queue methods

Instead of add() and remove(), queues commonly use:

offer()
poll()
peek()
element()
remove()
add()

You should know the difference between each pair:

offer() vs add()
poll() vs remove()
peek() vs element()
C. Queue implementations

You need to understand:

LinkedList
PriorityQueue
ArrayDeque

Each works differently.

D. PriorityQueue

This is where Comparable and Comparator become important again.

Example:

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

Insert:

pq.offer(50);
pq.offer(10);
pq.offer(40);
pq.offer(20);

Although you inserted:

50
10
40
20

When removing:

poll();

Output:

10
20
40
50

Why?

Because PriorityQueue is based on a Heap, not FIFO.

It orders elements according to priority.

E. Comparable and Comparator in Queue
For wrapper classes
PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

Integer already implements Comparable.

No extra work is needed.

For custom classes
class Student {

    int id;
    String name;
}

This won't work by default:

PriorityQueue<Student> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

Java doesn't know how to compare two Student objects.

You must either:

implement Comparable<Student>, or
provide a Comparator<Student>.

So the same comparison concepts you learned for sorting lists and TreeSet also apply to PriorityQueue.

F. equals() and hashCode()

Normal queues like:

LinkedList
ArrayDeque
PriorityQueue

do not use hashCode() internally to organize elements.

Unlike HashSet and HashMap, they don't store data in hash buckets.

However, your objects should still have correct equals() (and usually hashCode()) implementations if you want methods like contains() or remove(Object) to behave correctly for custom objects.

G. Internal working

You'll learn:

LinkedList Queue
Front

↓

10 → 20 → 30 → 40

               ↑
             Rear

Insertion happens at the rear.

Removal happens at the front.

Both operations are O(1).

PriorityQueue

Internally it is a Binary Heap, not a linked list.

You'll learn:

Parent node
Left child
Right child
Heapify up
Heapify down

This is one of the most common interview topics.

ArrayDeque

Internally it uses a resizable circular array.

It supports insertion and deletion efficiently from both ends.

H. Deque (Double Ended Queue)

A Deque allows operations at both the front and the rear.

Front <-------> Rear

You can:

addFirst()
addLast()
removeFirst()
removeLast()
I. Stack using Deque

In modern Java, Deque is recommended instead of the older Stack class.

Example:

Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);

System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 30

Here, push() and pop() use one end of the deque, giving LIFO (Last In, First Out) behavior.

Your Java Collection Roadmap
✅ List (you're almost done)
✅ Set
✅ Map
➜ Queue
➜ Deque
➜ PriorityQueue (Heap)
➜ ArrayDeque
➜ Stack using Deque
➜ Internal implementations and time complexities
➜ Interview questions and design decisions

From what I've seen in your questions over the last few days, you're trying to understand why Java is designed this way, not just memorize methods. That's exactly the right approach.

I would recommend learning Queue in the same style we covered Iterator and HashMap: starting from the real-world problem it solves, then its interface, implementations, internal data structures, time complexity, custom objects, Comparable/Comparator usage in PriorityQueue, and finally how Deque implements both queue and stack behavior. That sequence makes each concept build naturally on the previous one.


